title: For Sale:  Steyr Mannlicher HS .50 50 BMG with Nightforce scope, Pelican case, LaRue mount.
postcontent: I have for sale a real long range package for the serious .50 BMG shooter. I have put this together over the last year and have just found it to be too big of a caliber for my needs. I don't have the time, inclination, money, or skill to operate this as it should be, so I am moving on to closer range applications. This is the big Steyr HS 50. It is in good condition, some evidence of use and handling but overall in very good shape. I got it used and sent it to Steyr prior to shooting it for a factory inspection. Steyr‚Äôs gunsmith Herbert inspected it, gave it a clean bill of health and sent it back. I selected the Nightforce NXS 12-42X56 scope with the NPR-1 illuminated reticle, it has the sunshade and Nightforce lens cloth. Scope is in perfect condition, no scratches to lenses or finish, and function is perfect. Galileo observed the rings of Saturn using a telescope with a magnification of 20, this scope can observe .50 cal holes in varying targets a long way off! The NPR-1 reticle is very clean and unobtrusive, fine line gradients make ranging clear and concise, and the illuminated reticle makes low light shooting possible. I have it mounted on a LaRue QD LT107. This mount has 3 cams and a 20 MOA cant to take full advantage of this guns range capabilities. No need for lapping these rings, they are the best on the market, very precise and built like a tank. I have plumbed and leveled the reticle perpendicular to the bore axis, and torqued the mount screws to the advised 30 in/lbs. The whole gun breaks in half by two captured screws; the scope is mounted on a Picatinny rail on the barrel so zero is not affected. The muzzle brake and weight of this gun make recoil a slow push, the sound however will raise some eyebrows on the range. Trigger is two stage and factory set to 4 lbs. The Bi-pod is a work of art, very solid extensions, broad foot base, full swivel, quick disconnect/install, and easily stows along the barrel length. I lapped and installed a spacer between the Bi-pod and stock as there was some play there and could allow the recoil of the gun to jump the tooth on the QD mount. With the spacer installed it takes a slight push to get the Bi-pod to mount up or dismount and tightens the whole assembly up perfectly. Whole package is form fitted to fit into a Pelican 1750 case in OD green. It is a brand new case and is the only way to go with a set up like this. I am also including the tools for this gun and accessories. The LaRue tactical entry tool, useful for loosening the cams on the scope mount, the torx wrench for the scope screws, an extra screw for the scope mount, the 3/8 wrench for the cam tensioners, the T-handle wrench for the gun disassembly, and a canister of milspec multiviscosity M1A grease for use on gun parts in varying climates. I have shot M33 and M8 through this gun with groups as tight as 1 MOA at 300 yards. I know that is barely far enough for the powder to quit burning, but that is part of why I am selling it, I just don‚Äôt time to get to ranges that this thing is capable of. I am not much of a long range shooter and can‚Äôt really speak to what this gun is capable of. I have not shot it off anything but the Bi-pod, and have not run any truly precision ammo through it. Bore and chamber are clean with no evidence of mercuric primed ammo ever being used; brake is in perfect shape and the gun cycles great. This is a heavy package and not a set up for the inexperienced or faint of heart. Everything is sighted, turnkey and ready for someone who can appreciate its capabilities. I do have a cleaning set for it as well as a fair amount of ammo that I can work on price if buyer is interested.

title: For Sale:  L1A1 FAL
postcontent:
This is an early 90's Imbel century import of a real and uncommon New Zealand Air Force L1A1. A 1962 manufactured Australian\New Zealand Inch Pattern rifle on a top quality Imbel metric receiver. The barrel is prior to 1961 as per the "L" date code. Bore is bright and shiny. Barrel and gas block are Lithgow made, Aussie. Bolt and carrier are Aussie. Bolt has spent some time in a British FAL that was serial number UBA 117976. Stock is NZ air force with the brass disc. Has an Aussie folding charging handle which would be correct for an NZ. Having marked laminate hand guards. Originally this 1962 rifle would have had solid wood hand guards so the laminates are replacements, but the wood often cracked or were broken so the replacements would also be correct. Flash hider is British made by BSA in 1960. Front sling swivel and bolt hold open are British. Takes inch or metric mags. According to Skennertons book (as per the serial numbers) this rifle is/was part of a contract run for New Zealand. Comes with 2-20rd mags and 1-30rd mag. One 20rd mag and the 30rd mag are DSA mags. Original sling included

title: For Sale:  Magpul MOE Carbine Handguards
postcontent:
The Magpul MOE Hand Guard (Magpul Original Equipment) for AR15/M4 firearms with carbine-length gas systems combines the light weight of a standard hand guard with modular flexibility. Designed with versatility in mind, slots at the two, six, and ten o'clock positions allow the attachment of optional Picatinny rail sections and other accessories for mounting tactical lights, slings, grips, etc. Reinforced, heat-resistant polymer construction provides operational durability without the weight and expense of an aluminum rail hand guard. Front extensions and lower lip provides additional operator protection from hot front sight assembly.

Made in U.S.A.

Features
Replaces standard M4 Carbine-type plastic hand guards. Now compatible with most piston-driven as well as 'direct impingement' gas systems. Easy to install utilizing existing delta ring and round or triangular front hand guard retaining cap. Slots at the two, six, and ten o'clock positions for mounting MIL-STD-1913 Picatinny rails or other optional accessories. Reinforced, heat-resistant polymer construction. Integral riveted aluminum heat shield. Front lip and side extensions, shields hand from hot gas block. Relieved area at the top rear accommodates many overhanging optic mounts.
